JO  - Journal of Geriatric Psychiatry
AB  - A prospective study of 150 elderly patients (age >65) with major depressive disorder receiving either cognitive behavioral therapy (CBT) or standard care for 16 weeks. Depression severity was assessed using the Hamilton Depression Rating Scale. CBT group showed significantly greater improvement (mean reduction 12.4 points vs 5.2 points, p<0.01). Quality of life measures also improved more in the CBT group. No adverse events were reported. Findings suggest CBT is an effective and safe treatment option for late-life depression.
